Hmm, that log file doesn't seem to contain bits about the VM when it crashed. Annoyingly it's filled with tons of
((null):7924): Spice-Warning **: red_channel.c:546:red_channel_client_send_ping: getsockopt failed, Operation not supported
Probably a side effect of running as non-root. But it doesn't seem to the be the root issue. So if anyone else hits this crash again, please attach the qemu log file as well

I think my reading of the original backtrace makes me think it's an out-of-ram failure.
#2 error_propagate at util/error.c:173 #3 qemu_ram_alloc_internal at /usr/src/debug/qemu-2.3.0-rc3/exec.c:1544 that's checking for errors just after 'ram_block_add'
and looking inside ram_block_add the only place the error gets set is by phys_mem_alloc failing.
#4 qemu_ram_alloc at /usr/src/debug/qemu-2.3.0-rc3/exec.c:1558 #5 memory_region_init_ram at /usr/src/debug/qemu-2.3.0-rc3/memory.c:1138 #6 allocate_system_memory_nonnuma at /usr/src/debug/qemu-2.3.0-rc3/numa.c:341
In here we have: memory_region_init_ram(mr, owner, name, ram_size, &error_abort); and commit 49946538 started passing error_abort to that.
#7 memory_region_allocate_system_memory at /usr/src/debug/qemu-2.3.0-rc3/numa.c:354 #8 pc_memory_init at /usr/src/debug/qemu-2.3.0-rc3/hw/i386/pc.c:1248 #9 pc_init1 at /usr/src/debug/qemu-2.3.0-rc3/hw/i386/pc_piix.c:183
Dave
I am probably hitting this problem. If you need some information that may helps you, please let me know.

(In reply to Marcel Wysocki from comment #20) > I hit the bug simply by running > > [maci@mwysocki ~]$ qemu-system-or32 > qemu: fatal: Trying to execute code outside RAM or ROM at 0x08000000 > > PC=08000000 > R00=00000000 R01=00000000 R02=00000000 R03=00000000 > R04=00000000 R05=00000000 R06=00000000 R07=00000000 > R08=00000000 R09=00000000 R10=00000000 R11=00000000 > R12=00000000 R13=00000000 R14=00000000 R15=00000000 > R16=00000000 R17=00000000 R18=00000000 R19=00000000 > R20=00000000 R21=00000000 R22=00000000 R23=00000000 > R24=00000000 R25=00000000 R26=00000000 R27=00000000 > R28=00000000 R29=00000000 R30=00000000 R31=00000000 > Aborted (core dumped) > [maci@mwysocki ~]$ > > > all I did was scroll up and down a bit in the qemu window
Marcel: That's a different problem. This bug is only for a SIGABRT which includes memory_region_allocate_system_memory in the backtrace.

Yeah this abort() is just when too much ram has been requested. qemu previously did exit(1) here instead but that regressed. Markus has patches on qemu-devel to fix it but they touch a lot of files:
https://lists.nongnu.org/archive/html/qemu-devel/2015-09/msg03198.html
Those patches are in rawhide, so it should be 'fixed' there. But I think we just have to live with this problem for f23 and earlier.
